fp-io/src/lib.rs:571 — `read_csv_str` uses `record.get(idx).unwrap_or_default()` so when a CSV row has fewer columns than the header row, the missing columns are silently filled with empty strings (then parsed as missing/null via parse_scalar).

Pandas: `pd.read_csv` with default `on_bad_lines='error'` raises ParserError on ragged rows. The silent fill masks data corruption.

Surgical fix: replace `.unwrap_or_default()` with an explicit length check before the inner loop:
```rust
if record.len() != header_count {
    return Err(IoError::RaggedRow {
        row: row_count + 1,  // 1-indexed for user
        expected: header_count,
        actual: record.len(),
    });
}
```
Add IoError::RaggedRow variant. Add test with a CSV containing a short row.

May need a parallel `on_bad_lines` parameter for skip/warn modes in a follow-up; for now match pandas's strict default.

fp-frame/src/lib.rs:9558 — Rolling::max delegates to apply_rolling which doesn't pre-check nums.is_empty. With min_periods=0 and an all-missing window, the iter fold uses the identity f64::NEG_INFINITY → returns -∞ instead of NaN.

Same shape:
- Rolling::prod at line ~9747 returns 1.0 (empty product identity) instead of NaN
- Rolling::sum can return 0.0 (also identity) — but pandas actually returns 0.0 for sum, so OK
- Rolling::min already has an explicit `nums.is_empty()` guard (line 9527, 9540)

Pandas:
  >>> pd.Series([float('nan')]).rolling(1, min_periods=0).max()
  0    NaN

Surgical fix for max: inline the loop like Rolling::min did, OR wrap the agg closure to return NaN on empty:
```rust
pub fn max(&self) -> Result<Series, FrameError> {
    self.apply_rolling(
        |nums| {
            if nums.is_empty() {
                f64::NAN
            } else {
                nums.iter().copied().fold(f64::NEG_INFINITY, f64::max)
            }
        },
        self.series.name(),
    )
}
```

Apply same wrap to prod (NaN on empty, since 1.0 is wrong for "no observations").

Tests: Series([NaN]).rolling(1, min_periods=0).max() == [NaN].

fp-conformance/src/lib.rs:26831-26836 (test fp_frame_first_wave_public_panics_are_documented) requires fp-frame/src/lib.rs to contain a specific # Panics docstring directly above DataFrame::last_offset:

```
/// # Panics
///
/// Panics if the DataFrame reports non-empty but its index has no last
/// label, which indicates internal index corruption.
pub fn last_offset(&self, offset: &str) -> Result<Self, FrameError> {
```

Currently the # Panics docstring is placed above `pub fn last` (line 33356), but `pub fn last_offset` (line 33361) only carries `/// Explicit alias for [Self::last].`.

Fix: add the # Panics docstring directly above pub fn last_offset (in addition to keeping it on pub fn last, or moving it). The test enforces docstring placement so callers reading the rustdoc for last_offset see the panic contract.

This was likely a partial refactor where someone added Self::last as an alias but only documented one of the two functions.

fp-frame/src/lib.rs:33514 DataFrame::drop has asymmetric behavior:
- axis=1 (drop columns): validates each name exists, raises CompatibilityRejected when missing (line 33519).
- axis=0 (drop rows): filters by drop_set membership but does NOT validate that every requested label appears in the index. Missing labels are silently skipped.

Pandas raises KeyError in both axes by default.

Surgical fix at line 33536: after building drop_set, validate each requested label exists in the index, mirroring the axis=1 path.

```rust
let index_set: HashSet<&IndexLabel> = self.index.labels().iter().collect();
for label in &drop_set {
    if !index_set.contains(label) {
        return Err(FrameError::CompatibilityRejected(format!(
            "drop: label {label:?} not found in index"
        )));
    }
}
```

Also preserves index name via Index::new(...).rename_index(self.index.name()) — likely already needed (separate fix or fold in).

Tests: DataFrame.drop(["missing"], axis=0) returns Err; valid drops succeed.

fp-frame/src/lib.rs:31996 reduce_rows filters numeric_cols to Int64/Float64/Bool only:
```rust
let numeric_cols: Vec<&str> = self.column_order.iter().filter(|c| {
    let dt = self.columns[c.as_str()].dtype();
    dt == DType::Int64 || dt == DType::Float64 || dt == DType::Bool
}).map(|s| s.as_str()).collect();
```
This silently drops Timedelta64 columns from sum_axis1/mean_axis1/min_axis1/max_axis1/std_axis1/var_axis1/etc. pandas df.sum(axis=1) on a Timedelta64-only DataFrame returns Timedelta64 row sums.

This is a structural fix: reduce_rows operates on f64. To preserve Timedelta64 for axis=1 sum/mean/min/max specifically, we'd need a separate Timedelta-aware row-reducer. For now, the smaller surgery is to allow Timedelta64 columns through the filter (so to_f64() error path triggers cleanly) OR to detect uniformly-Timedelta DataFrame and route to a Timedelta-typed path.

Smallest surgical: when ALL columns are Timedelta64, add a dedicated row-reducer for sum/mean/min/max that operates on i64 ns and emits Scalar::Timedelta64 row values. For mixed types or non-{sum,mean,min,max} funcs, keep the existing filter.

fp-frame/src/lib.rs:4217 — Series::drop(labels) filters self.index.labels by `drop_set.contains(lbl)`, silently passing through labels that don't exist in the index. Pandas raises:

  KeyError: "['x'] not found in axis"

Surgical fix: before the filter loop, validate that all requested labels exist:
```rust
let index_set: HashSet<&IndexLabel> = self.index.labels().iter().collect();
let missing: Vec<&IndexLabel> = labels.iter().filter(|l| !index_set.contains(l)).collect();
if !missing.is_empty() {
    return Err(FrameError::CompatibilityRejected(format!(
        "drop: labels {:?} not found in index", missing
    )));
}
```

This matches pandas's default behavior (errors='raise'). An `errors='ignore'` variant could be added later via a separate method.

Same pattern likely exists in DataFrame::drop(labels, axis=0) — separate bead.

Tests: Series::drop on a missing label returns Err; valid drops still succeed.

fp-frame/src/lib.rs:9718 and :9732 — Rolling::last calls `.last().expect("non-empty after min_periods")` on `nums` (collected non-missing window values). If min_periods=0 and the window is all-NaN, the guard `nums.len() < self.min_periods` is false (0 < 0 = false), the window_slice length check passes, and `.last()` is called on an empty Vec — PANIC.

Trigger: `Series::from_values([NaN, NaN]).rolling(2, Some(0)).last()`.

Pandas returns NaN for such windows (no valid observations).

Surgical fix: change the guard to also catch empty nums:
```rust
if nums.is_empty() || nums.len() < self.min_periods || window_slice.len() < self.window {
    out.push(Scalar::Null(NullKind::NaN));
} else {
    out.push(Scalar::Float64(*nums.last().unwrap()));
}
```

Apply to both center and non-center branches.

Sister method `first()` likely has the same bug — check that too. Also `Rolling::min/max` may have similar empty-nums vulnerabilities.

Tests: rolling(2, Some(0)).last() on [NaN, NaN] returns [NaN, NaN] without panic.

Skill: /mock-code-finder — silent stub via to_f64-else-passthrough.

fp-frame Series::clip_with_series (crates/fp-frame/src/lib.rs:4727) falls back to pushing val.clone() when to_f64 fails. Scalar::to_f64 fails for Timedelta64 (returns TypeError::NonNumericValue). Result: clip_with_series on a Timedelta64 series silently passes every value through unchanged, ignoring the lower/upper bounds entirely.

Pandas clips Timedelta64 with Timedelta64 bounds element-wise:
  >>> pd.Series([pd.Timedelta('5h'), pd.Timedelta('30m')]).clip(
          lower=pd.Series([pd.Timedelta('1h'), pd.Timedelta('1h')]))
  0    0 days 05:00:00
  1    0 days 01:00:00

fp-frame returns the input unchanged.

Sister to the recently-shipped Utf8 fix (br-frankenpandas-98b6e). Same shape: when val matches a non-numeric variant, fall through to a typed branch instead of silently no-op'ing.

Fix: add a Timedelta64 branch right after the Utf8 fast path (line 4707):
  if let Scalar::Timedelta64(nanos) = val {
      if *nanos == Timedelta::NAT { out.push(val.clone()); continue; }
      let mut clipped: i64 = *nanos;
      // lower bound (if Timedelta64 and not NAT) → max
      // upper bound (if Timedelta64 and not NAT) → min
      out.push(Scalar::Timedelta64(clipped));
      continue;
  }

Tests:
- clip_with_series on Timedelta64 with Timedelta64 lower bound clips to bound when below.
- clip_with_series on Timedelta64 with Timedelta64 upper bound clips to bound when above.
- clip_with_series on Timedelta64 with NAT bound passes through unclipped (same row).
- existing numeric/Utf8 clip_with_series tests remain green.

After br-frankenpandas-yy0ks made var() return Scalar::Timedelta64 for Timedelta input, Series::std at line 5681 now falls into `other => Ok(other)` and returns the variance unchanged instead of sqrt(variance).

```rust
pub fn std(&self) -> Result<Scalar, FrameError> {
    match self.var()? {
        Scalar::Float64(v) => Ok(Scalar::Float64(v.sqrt())),
        other => Ok(other),  // BUG: Timedelta64 var falls through unchanged
    }
}
```

pandas pd.Series([td1, td2]).std() returns sqrt of variance. Mirror fp-types nanstd j8ntk path: for Timedelta64 var, compute (ns_var as f64).sqrt() then clamp into i64 ns. Surgical (~5 lines).

fp-columnar/src/lib.rs:368-376 — from_scalars with DType::Categorical:
```rust
DType::Categorical => {
    let data: Vec<i64> = values
        .iter()
        .map(|v| match v {
            Scalar::Int64(i) => *i,
            _ => -1,
        })
        .collect();
    Self::Int64(data)
}
```

Non-Int64 scalars (Utf8, Float64, Bool, Null, Timedelta64) are silently mapped to code -1. Pandas raises on dtype-mismatch when materializing a Categorical column from incompatible scalars.

Surgical fix: switch the catch-all from `_ => -1` to return an explicit ColumnError (or propagate via try_collect). For Null/missing, use the established missing sentinel rather than -1 (which is a valid code in most Categorical encodings). For other dtypes, return Err.

Tests: from_scalars with Vec<Scalar> mixing Int64 and Utf8 against DType::Categorical returns an error. Null-only stays valid (uses missing sentinel). Pure Int64 input still works.

fp-join/src/lib.rs:659-664 (or near; verify) — in collect_composite_keys / JoinKeyComponent:
```rust
fp_types::Scalar::Float64(v) if !v.is_nan() => {
    if *v == v.trunc() && *v >= i64::MIN as f64 && *v < 9223372036854775808.0 {
        JoinKeyComponent::Present(IndexLabel::Int64(*v as i64))
    } else {
        JoinKeyComponent::FloatBits(v.to_bits())
    }
}
```

When merging left(Int64 key) with right(Float64 key with integer values), this silently unifies them as IndexLabel::Int64, allowing the merge to proceed. Pandas raises ValueError on key dtype mismatch.

Surgical fix: add a dtype-compatibility check before the join. Compare the dtypes of corresponding key columns; if they disagree (Int64 vs Float64, Utf8 vs Int64, etc.), return Err with a pandas-style "key dtype mismatch" message.

This may break existing tests that rely on the silent coercion — investigate before shipping.

Tests: merge with mismatched key dtypes returns CompatibilityRejected; matching dtypes still merge cleanly.

fp-frame/src/lib.rs:32038 DataFrame::reduce_numeric (and std_agg_ddof:31842, var_agg_ddof:31860) filters columns to Int64/Float64 only via:
```rust
if col.dtype() != DType::Int64 && col.dtype() != DType::Float64 {
    continue;
}
```
This silently drops Timedelta64 columns from DataFrame::sum/mean/min/max/std/var/median/prod aggregations. pandas DataFrame.sum() on mixed Int64+Timedelta64 columns includes both — Timedelta64 results are returned as Timedelta scalars in the output Series.

Series::sum/mean/min/max/std/var/median now preserve Timedelta64 dtype (br-28lgk, edmsd, erobu, 7iz85, j0ilf, yy0ks, rbt10). Add DType::Timedelta64 to the allowed-dtype list for sum/mean/min/max/std/var/median; keep skew/kurtosis/sem filter (they return f64 directly and Series sem/skew/kurtosis only support numeric).

Surgical (one-file edit).

fp-frame/src/lib.rs:33651 — DataFrame::insert(loc, name, column) silently clamps the position:
  let loc = loc.min(self.column_order.len());

Pandas: insert(loc=N, ...) where N > len(df.columns) raises:
  ValueError: invalid insertion position 5 for DataFrame with 3 columns

Surgical fix: replace the clamp with a bounds check + error, mirroring isetitem's pattern at line 33665:
```rust
if loc > self.column_order.len() {
    return Err(FrameError::CompatibilityRejected(format!(
        "insert: loc {loc} out of bounds for width {}",
        self.column_order.len()
    )));
}
```

Note: insert allows loc == ncols (append at end) per pandas, so use `loc > ncols` not `>=`.

Tests: insert on a 3-col DataFrame with loc=5 returns CompatibilityRejected. Existing in-range inserts stay green.

fp-types/src/lib.rs:657 — Timedelta::parse compound path:
```rust
let nanos = (num * multiplier as f64).round() as i64;
total = total.checked_add(nanos).ok_or(TimedeltaError::Overflow)?;
```

For hostile/large input like `"1e100 days"` or `"9.999e30 seconds"`, the f64 multiplication produces ±INFINITY or values past 2^63. The `.round() as i64` cast silently saturates to i64::MAX (or i64::MIN for negatives) — masking the overflow. The downstream checked_add doesn't catch it because the saturated value is technically additive-valid.

Pandas: `pd.Timedelta("1e100 days")` raises an OverflowError / ValueError.

Surgical fix at fp-types/src/lib.rs:657:
```rust
let product = num * multiplier as f64;
if !product.is_finite() || product.abs() >= 9223372036854775808.0 {
    return Err(TimedeltaError::Overflow);
}
let nanos = product.round() as i64;
```

Tests: Timedelta::parse("1e100 days").is_err(); Timedelta::parse("9999999999999999999 days").is_err(); existing well-formed parses ("1.5 hours", "30 seconds", etc.) stay green.

## Finding (consistency lens, sister gap to br-0d6f8 / br-db6ec)

Series::unstack (line 6968) builds row_keys and col_keys with
Vec::contains:

  if !row_keys.contains(&row_key) {
      row_keys.push(row_key.clone());
  }
  if !col_keys.contains(&col_key) {
      col_keys.push(col_key.clone());
  }

For n entries with k unique row keys and j unique col keys:
O(n × k + n × j). For n=1M, k=j=1000: ~2×10⁹ comparisons just for
key-set construction. Same shape as br-0d6f8 (Series::drop) and
br-db6ec (DataFrame::append column union).

## Fix

HashSet for membership tracking, parallel insertion-ordered Vec
for first-seen ordering preservation:

  let mut row_keys: Vec<String> = Vec::new();
  let mut row_seen: HashSet<String> = HashSet::new();
  let mut col_keys: Vec<String> = Vec::new();
  let mut col_seen: HashSet<String> = HashSet::new();
  ...
  if row_seen.insert(row_key.clone()) {
      row_keys.push(row_key.clone());
  }
  if col_seen.insert(col_key.clone()) {
      col_keys.push(col_key.clone());
  }

Total: O(n) amortized. Insertion order preserved.

## Tests

- unstack on small composite-key Series produces expected
  rows × columns DataFrame (regression guard)
- unstack on wide input (5K entries with mix of keys) — correctness
  asserted (perf scaling implied by test size)
- existing unstack tests remain green

## Why surfaced

/modes-of-reasoning consistency lens — having fixed Series::drop
(0d6f8) and DataFrame::append (db6ec), the same Vec::contains
pattern in unstack was the natural sister. Closing the family of
hot-loop linear-scan patterns continues.

## Finding (hot-loop linear-scan pattern, sister gap to db6ec)

Series::drop (line 3572) iterates self.index labels and checks
membership in the user-provided drop list via Vec::contains:

  for (i, lbl) in self.index.labels().iter().enumerate() {
      if !labels.contains(lbl) {  // ← O(|labels|) per iteration
          new_labels.push(lbl.clone());
          new_values.push(self.column.values()[i].clone());
      }
  }

For n self-labels × m drop-labels: O(n × m). For n=1M, m=10K:
~10¹⁰ comparisons. Same shape as br-db6ec (DataFrame::append column
union) and the broader scan-and-find quadratic family.

IndexLabel derives Hash + Eq (line 86 of fp-index/src/lib.rs), so
HashSet<&IndexLabel> is a drop-in.

## Fix

  let drop_set: HashSet<&IndexLabel> = labels.iter().collect();
  for (i, lbl) in self.index.labels().iter().enumerate() {
      if !drop_set.contains(lbl) {
          new_labels.push(lbl.clone());
          new_values.push(self.column.values()[i].clone());
      }
  }

Total: O(n + m) — m to build the set, n × O(1) lookups.

## Tests

- drop with disjoint labels (no-op when label not in index)
- drop with overlapping labels removes the matching entries
- drop preserves first-occurrence ordering for non-dropped entries
- regression guard: existing drop tests remain green
- wide-input scaling test (5K labels, 500 dropped)

## Why surfaced

/deadlock-finder-and-fixer — same shape as the recently-fixed
column-union pattern (db6ec) and the scan-and-find quadratic
family (7c7d0/15f51/d8d9d/etc.). Series::drop is the natural sister
gap on labels-instead-of-columns axis.

## Finding (porting pandas Utf8 cumsum behavior)

Series::cumsum (line 5119) has Int64 + Bool specialized branches and
falls through to a Float64-only path that calls to_f64 — which errors
on Utf8.

Pandas:
  pd.Series(['a','b','c']).cumsum() → ['a', 'ab', 'abc'] (object dtype)

fp-frame: returns Err.

Sister gap to br-c4898 (cummin/cummax Utf8) — pandas defines a
'cumulative concatenate' for cumsum on strings, mirroring how
cumsum is 'cumulative add' for numbers.

## Reproducer

  let s = Series::from_values("x",
      vec![0_i64.into(), 1_i64.into(), 2_i64.into()],
      vec![Scalar::Utf8("a".into()), Scalar::Utf8("b".into()),
           Scalar::Utf8("c".into())])?;
  s.cumsum();
    // before: Err (to_f64 fails on Utf8)
    // after:  Ok([Utf8("a"), Utf8("ab"), Utf8("abc")])

## Fix

Add a Utf8 branch (after the Bool branch) that accumulates
concatenated strings:

  if !values.is_empty() && values.iter().all(|v| matches!(v, Scalar::Utf8(_))) {
      let mut acc = String::new();
      let mut out = Vec::with_capacity(values.len());
      for value in values {
          if let Scalar::Utf8(s) = value {
              acc.push_str(s);
              out.push(Scalar::Utf8(acc.clone()));
          }
      }
      return Self::from_values(...);
  }

Same shape as the Int64 and Bool branches; same shape as the
cummin/cummax Utf8 fix from c4898.

## Tests

- cumsum on Utf8 concatenates: ['a','b','c'] → ['a','ab','abc']
- cumsum on Utf8 with empty strings: ['','b','c'] → ['','b','bc']
- cumsum on single-element Utf8 series: ['hello'] → ['hello']
- existing Int64/Bool/Float64 cumsum tests must remain green

## Why surfaced

/porting-to-rust applied to the recent Utf8 fix wave (c4898/83c2a/
7db78/9978d/ff284). cumsum on Utf8 is the natural completion of
the cumulative-op set.

fd90.74-123 README audit — Error Architecture table at lines 821-830. Two rows list 'LengthMismatch' as if it were a unit variant, alongside other struct-variant entries that correctly use braces:

  | IndexError | ... | OutOfBounds { position, length }, LengthMismatch, ... |
  | FrameError | ... | LengthMismatch, DuplicateIndexUnsupported, ... |

But both are struct variants:
- crates/fp-frame/src/lib.rs:111 — FrameError::LengthMismatch { index_len, column_len }
- crates/fp-index/src/lib.rs:1344 — IndexError::LengthMismatch { expected, actual, context }

The README has been progressively normalized (see fd90.101 for MissingIndexColumn). 'LengthMismatch' is the last remaining unit-typed-looking entry that's actually a struct variant.

Also: TypeError row shows IncompatibleDtypes { left, right } correctly with braces, so the README convention is established — the LengthMismatch entries just weren't updated.

Fix:
- IndexError row: LengthMismatch → LengthMismatch { expected, actual, context }
- FrameError row: LengthMismatch → LengthMismatch { index_len, column_len }

Pure README change.

**Severity:** MEDIUM (consistency/parity gap; backend errors leak through with backend-specific messages instead of typed client-side errors).

**Finding:** `validate_sql_identifier_length` is only called from `write_sql_with_options` (line ~6760: validates table/column/index/schema names against `conn.max_identifier_length()` before DDL). The read-path and DROP-path query builders SKIP length validation:

- `sql_select_all_query_in_schema` (line 4927) — only `validate_sql_table_name` (shape only)
- `sql_select_columns_query_in_schema` (line 4967) — only `validate_sql_table_name` + `validate_sql_column_name` (shape only)
- `sql_create_table_query_in_schema` (line 5031) — only `validate_sql_table_name` (shape only)
- `sql_insert_rows_query_in_schema` (line 5069) — only `validate_sql_table_name` (shape only)
- `sql_drop_table_query_in_schema` (line 5168) — only `validate_sql_table_name` (shape only)
- `default truncate_table` (line 4216) — only `validate_sql_table_name` (shape only)

**Impact:** On a backend with `max_identifier_length` set (PG=63, MySQL=64, MSSQL=128), passing an over-cap identifier produces a SELECT/INSERT/DROP statement that the backend rejects at parse time with a backend-specific error like `identifier "..." will be truncated to 63 characters` (PG WARNING) or `Identifier name too long` (MySQL). Users see backend leakage instead of the clean typed `IoError::Sql("invalid X name '...': length N exceeds backend identifier limit (M)")` that `write_sql_with_options` produces.

**Reproducer (sketch, would need test infra):**
```rust
struct PgCap63 { /* supports_schemas=true, max_identifier_length=Some(63) */ }
let conn = PgCap63;
let long_name = "a".repeat(100);
// write_sql_with_options(&frame, &conn, &long_name, ...) → typed IoError::Sql about 63-char limit ✓
// read_sql_table(&conn, &long_name) → builds SELECT that PG rejects with raw error ✗
// sql_drop_table_query_in_schema(&conn, &long_name, None) → builds DROP that PG rejects ✗
```

**Suggested fix:** add `validate_sql_identifier_length(name, conn.max_identifier_length(), kind)` to each of the 6 query-builder functions above, mirroring what `write_sql_with_options` already does. Add a regression test in the fd90.12 quoting matrix style verifying that `sql_select_columns_query_in_schema` rejects over-cap identifiers per dialect.

**Discoverer:** cc-pandas (claude-opus-4-7) during review-mode P3 cross-review of e129119/fc4ba86/48a2f0b SQL query builders on 2026-05-02. Spotted while reviewing my own e129119 quoting matrix tests — they verify `validate_sql_identifier_length` behavior in isolation but the function isn't called by the builders themselves on the read/drop/create/insert paths.

## Finding (deadlock-finder, hot-loop linear-scan pattern)

DataFrame::value_counts (crates/fp-frame/src/lib.rs:23771) builds
composite-key tuples per row and searches for matches via a linear
iter_mut().find():

  for i in 0..self.len() {
      // build key_parts: Vec<ScalarKey<'_>> from N columns
      if let Some((_, _, count)) = key_counts
          .iter_mut().find(|(k, _, _)| *k == key_parts)
      {
          *count += 1;
      } else {
          key_counts.push((key_parts, key_label, 1));
      }
  }

For n input rows and k unique combinations: O(n × k). For n=1M,
k=100K: ~10¹⁰ comparisons. Same shape as br-7c7d0 (Series::value_counts)
which I fixed earlier; the DataFrame variant was missed.

## Fix

Vec<ScalarKey> is Hash + Eq + PartialEq (ScalarKey derives all three),
so a HashMap<Vec<ScalarKey>, usize> index is a drop-in. Same approach
as br-7c7d0: parallel insertion-ordered Vec for first-seen-order, plus
HashMap from composite-key → index in the Vec.

  let mut key_counts: Vec<(Vec<ScalarKey>, String, i64)> = Vec::new();
  let mut idx_map: HashMap<Vec<ScalarKey<'_>>, usize> = HashMap::new();
  for i in 0..n {
      let key_parts = ...;
      match idx_map.get(&key_parts) {
          Some(&idx) => key_counts[idx].2 += 1,
          None => {
              idx_map.insert(key_parts.clone(), key_counts.len());
              key_counts.push((key_parts, label, 1));
          }
      }
  }

## Reproducer (perf, not correctness)

  let df = ... 1M rows × 3 cols, ~100K unique combinations ...;
  df.value_counts();
    // before: minutes
    // after:  <1s

## Tests

- value_counts on small DataFrame returns correct combination counts
- value_counts preserves descending sort by count (stable on ties)
- existing dataframe value_counts tests must remain green
- regression guard: 5K rows × 3 cols correctness check (perf scaling
  implied by test size)

## Why surfaced

/deadlock-finder-and-fixer applied to remaining hot-loop linear-scan
patterns. Sister gap to:
- 7c7d0 (Series::value_counts O(n²) → O(n))
- 15f51 (Series::unique/nunique)
- d8d9d (Series::duplicated/drop_duplicates)
- 5110c (Series::map/replace)
- f7201 (Series::isin)
- cec8f (Series::mode_with_dropna)
- 6ce89 (DataFrame::nunique_with_dropna)

DataFrame::value_counts is the natural completion of this pattern.

## Finding (perf lens, sister gap to br-15f51)

DataFrame::nunique_with_dropna (line 26671) iterates columns and calls
distinct_values(col.values(), dropna).len() per column:

